'''M72/AS01<sub>E</sub>''' is an experimental [[tuberculosis]] vaccine. If approved, it would be the first [[vaccine]] for tuberculosis in more than a century after the [[BCG vaccine]].<ref name=propublica/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tozer |first1=Lilly |title=Promising tuberculosis vaccine gets US$550-million shot in the arm |journal=Nature |date=28 June 2023 |doi=10.1038/d41586-023-02171-x |pmid=37380847 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-02171-x |language=en|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

The vaccine consists of two main ingredients. The [[antigen]] part is M72, a [[recombinant protein|recombinant]] [[fusion protein]] derived from the sequences of two ''M. tuberculosis'' antigens (Mtb32A {{UniProt|O07175}} and Mtb39A {{UniProt|L7N675}}). The adjuvant part is AS01<sub>E</sub>, a combination of [[QS-21]], cholesterol, and monophosphoryl lipid A (MPL).<ref name=2bfinal/>

It was initially developed by [[GSK plc]] and funded by non-profits and governments due to the limited commercial potential of tuberculosis vaccines, which are mainly needed in poor countries. The vaccine candidate completed a [[Phase II clinical trial]] in 2018, but its development was stalled thereafter due to negotiations between GSK, which was uninterested in the late stage development of the vaccine candidate, and non-commercial backers. After almost two years, the company concluded an agreement with the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Medical Research Institute]]. The Phase III trial is funded by the [[Wellcome Trust]] (up to US$150 million) and the [[Gates Foundation]] (the remaining around US$400 million). It is scheduled to begin in 2024 with results available in 2028. One issue in developing the vaccine is the need for [[QS-21]] bark extract from the tree ''[[Quillaja saponaria]]'' that is used in combination with [[monophosphoryl lipid A]] as an [[immunologic adjuvant]]. This adjuvant is used by several other GSK vaccines—especially the [[Shingrix|shingles vaccine]] that is more profitable—and GSK owns most of the world's supply.<ref name=propublica>{{cite news |last1=Barry-Jester |first1=Anna Maria |title=How a Big Pharma Company Stalled a Potentially Lifesaving Vaccine in Pursuit of Bigger Profits |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-big-pharma-company-stalled-tuberculosis-vaccine-to-pursue-bigger-profits |access-date=18 November 2023 |work=ProPublica |date=4 October 2023 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Press Release: Funding Late-Stage Development of M72 TB Vaccine Candidate |url=https://www.gatesfoundation.org/ideas/media-center/press-releases/2023/06/funding-commitment-m72-tb-vaccine-candidate |website=Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation |access-date=18 November 2023 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=2bfinal>{{cite journal |last1=Tait |first1=Dereck R. |last2=Hatherill |first2=Mark |last3=Van Der Meeren |first3=Olivier |last4=Ginsberg |first4=Ann M. |last5=Van Brakel |first5=Elana |last6=Salaun |first6=Bruno |last7=Scriba |first7=Thomas J. |last8=Akite |first8=Elaine J. |last9=Ayles |first9=Helen M. |last10=Bollaerts |first10=Anne |last11=Demoitié |first11=Marie-Ange |last12=Diacon |first12=Andreas |last13=Evans |first13=Thomas G. |last14=Gillard |first14=Paul |last15=Hellström |first15=Elizabeth |last16=Innes |first16=James C. |last17=Lempicki |first17=Maria |last18=Malahleha |first18=Mookho |last19=Martinson |first19=Neil |last20=Mesia Vela |first20=Doris |last21=Muyoyeta |first21=Monde |last22=Nduba |first22=Videlis |last23=Pascal |first23=Thierry G. |last24=Tameris |first24=Michele |last25=Thienemann |first25=Friedrich |last26=Wilkinson |first26=Robert J. |last27=Roman |first27=François |title=Final Analysis of a Trial of M72/AS01 E Vaccine to Prevent Tuberculosis |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=19 December 2019 |volume=381 |issue=25 |pages=2429–2439 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1909953|pmid=31661198 |doi-access=free |hdl=10044/1/74245 |hdl-access=free }} &ndash; phase 2b trial</ref>

